<TITLE> PM to address world food summit </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Rome, 16 November 2009 (bdnews24.com)  Prime minister Sheikh Hasina will address a World Summit on Food Security that opens in Rome Monday aiming to give new momentum to the fight against hunger and malnutrition affecting 1.02 billion people. The summit, to be attended by more than 50 heads of state and government. Pope Benedict XVI will deliver a keynote speech while UN secretary-general Ban Ki Moon and FAO director-general Jacques Diouf will also address the Summit on the opening day. Sheikh Hasina will deliver her speech in the afternoon (local time). She is scheduled to have bilateral talks with FAO chief Jaques Diouf the same day. During her three-day stay in Italy, Hasina will also participate in a roundtable meeting on `Climate change adaptation and mitigation challenges for agriculture and food security'. She will act as the vice-president of the international roundtable. The Bangladesh delegation to Rome includes agriculture minister Matia Chowdhury, food and disaster management minister Md. Abdur Razzaque and foreign minister Dipu Moni. How to feed the world FAO has convened the Nov 16-18 Summit in a bid to marshal political will behind increased investment in agriculture and a reinvigorated international effort to combat hunger. Participating countries will adopt a Summit Declaration on the first day. Three important events in October prepared the ground for the Summit, says FAO. A High-Level Expert Forum on How to Feed the World in 2050 examined policy options that governments should consider adopting to ensure that the world population can be fed when it nears its peak of nearly 9.2 billion people in the middle of this century. The Committee on World Food Security considered reforms that will enable it to play a much more effective role in the global governance of food security. The theme of World Food Day (Oct 16) this year was how to ensure food security in times of crisis. Ahead of the Summit, FAO also launched an online campaign, www.1billionhungry.org, calling on the general public to sign a call for eradicating hunger, and invited people to go on a "hunger strike against hunger" on to show solidarity. Hours before the opening of the Summit, Jacques Diouf and Ban Ki-moon joined the hunger strike on Sunday in solidarity with the one billion humans around the world who go hungry every 
